          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
    A <html:strong>metric space</html:strong> is a pair <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, d)]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a set and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d : X \times  X \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is a function called a <html:strong>metric</html:strong>, satisfying for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x, y, z \in  X]]></fr:tex>:
</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, y) \geq  0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, y) = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = y]]></fr:tex> (positive definiteness).</html:li>
    <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, y) = d(y, x)]]></fr:tex> (symmetry).</html:li>
    <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, z) \leq  d(x, y) + d(y, z)]]></fr:tex> (triangle inequality).</html:li></html:ol>
            <html:p>
    Every metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, d)]]></fr:tex> induces a <fr:link href="/gtop-0002/" title="Topological Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0002/" display-uri="gtop-0002" type="local">topology</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, called the <html:strong>metric topology</html:strong>, where the open sets are unions of <fr:link href="/gtop-000S/" title="Open Ball" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000S/" display-uri="gtop-000S" type="local">open balls</fr:link>.
</html:p>
