            <fr:title text="Open Set">Open Set</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, \tau )]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/gtop-0002/" title="Topological Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0002/" display-uri="gtop-0002" type="local">topological space</fr:link>. A subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U \subseteq  X]]></fr:tex> is called <html:strong>open</html:strong> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U \in  \tau ]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
    In a <fr:link href="/gtop-0004/" title="Euclidean Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0004/" display-uri="gtop-0004" type="local">Euclidean space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U \subseteq  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> is <html:strong>open</html:strong> if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  U]]></fr:tex>, there exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon  > 0]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B(x, \epsilon ) \subseteq  U]]></fr:tex>. More generally, in any <fr:link href="/gtop-0003/" title="Metric Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0003/" display-uri="gtop-0003" type="local">metric space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, d)]]></fr:tex>, a set is open if it is a union of <fr:link href="/gtop-000S/" title="Open Ball" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000S/" display-uri="gtop-000S" type="local">open balls</fr:link>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
    The <fr:link href="/gtop-0004/" title="Euclidean Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0004/" display-uri="gtop-0004" type="local">Euclidean</fr:link> definition is a special case where the topology is induced by the metric <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x, y) = \lVert  x - y \rVert ]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
